🧠 LESSON 1: VARIABLES, DATA TYPES & TYPE HINTS

🧩 1. Variables in Python

A variable is a named reference to a value stored in memory.
Python doesn’t need you to declare the type — it figures it out dynamically at runtime.

python
x = 10
name = "Fuzail"
is_active = True

🔍 Key Points

ConceptDescriptionExample
Dynamic TypingYou can assign any type to a variable at runtime.x = 5; x = "hello" ✅
Case Sensitivityname ≠ Name—
Variable NamingMust start with a letter or _ and contain letters, numbers, or _.user_age, _count ✅
Multiple AssignmentYou can assign several variables at once.a, b, c = 1, 2, 3
Swapping ValuesPythonic swap without temp variable.a, b = b, a

🧠 Memory Note

  • In Python, variables are references (pointers) to objects in memory.

  • When you write a = 5, a points to an integer object 5 stored in memory.

🔢 2. Python’s Core Data Types

TypeExampleDescription
intx = 42Whole numbers (unlimited size).
floaty = 3.14Decimal numbers.
boolis_valid = TrueLogical True/False values.
strname = "Fuzail"Sequence of Unicode characters.
listnums = [1, 2, 3]Ordered, mutable collection.
tuplecoords = (10, 20)Ordered, immutable collection.
setunique = {1, 2, 3}Unordered, unique elements.
dictuser = {"name": "Fuzail", "age": 20}Key-value pairs.
NoneTypevalue = NoneRepresents “no value”.

🔍 3. Type Checking & Conversion

Check Type

python
x = 5
print(type(x))        # <class 'int'>
print(isinstance(x, int))  # True

Convert Between Types

python
float(3)      # 3.0
int(3.9)      # 3
str(123)      # "123"
list("abc")   # ['a', 'b', 'c']
tuple([1,2])  # (1, 2)
set([1,1,2])  # {1, 2}

🧮 4. Type Hints (Modern Python 3.5+)

Type hints let you specify expected types — extremely useful for problem solving and team projects.
They don’t affect runtime but improve readability and IDE support.

python
age: int = 21
name: str = "Fuzail"
pi: float = 3.14159
is_student: bool = True

Function Type Hints

python
def greet(name: str, age: int) -> str:
    return f"Hello {name}, you are {age} years old!"

  • Parameters and return type are both annotated.

  • Tools like mypy can statically check correctness.

Complex Hints

python
from typing import List, Tuple, Dict, Set

numbers: List[int] = [1, 2, 3]
pairs: List[Tuple[int, str]] = [(1, "one"), (2, "two")]
grades: Dict[str, float] = {"Ali": 90.5, "Sara": 88.0}
unique_nums: Set[int] = {1, 2, 3}

⚙️ 5. Mutable vs Immutable Types

Mutable (Can Change)Immutable (Cannot Change)
listint
dictfloat
setstr
—tuple
python
# Mutable
nums = [1, 2, 3]
nums.append(4)       # changes same object

# Immutable
name = "Fuzail"
name.upper()         # creates new string

📎 Why this matters:
When solving problems, mutable types can be updated efficiently (e.g. building lists), while immutable ones are safe for dictionary keys or hash-based operations.

🧠 6. Python is Object-Oriented

Everything in Python is an object, even numbers and functions.

python
x = 10
print(x.bit_length())   # int has methods too

So when you do something like x + y, Python internally calls:

python
x.__add__(y)

🧰 7. Useful Built-in Functions

FunctionUse
type(obj)Get type of object
id(obj)Memory address of object
isinstance(obj, type)Check if object is instance of a class
dir(obj)List all methods/attributes
help(obj)Show documentation

🧩 LESSON 2: LISTS IN PYTHON

1️⃣ What is a List?

A list is a dynamic, ordered, and mutable sequence of items.
It’s one of the most used data structures for LeetCode problems because it supports:

  • random access,

  • iteration,

  • easy modification, and

  • flexible size changes.

python
from typing import List

numbers: List[int] = [1, 2, 3, 4]

✅ Key Features

PropertyDescriptionExample
OrderedElements keep their order[1, 2, 3]
MutableCan be changed after creation.append(4)
Allows Duplicates[1, 1, 2] valid—
HeterogeneousCan store mixed types (but avoid for LeetCode)[1, "Hi", 3.5]

2️⃣ Creating Lists

python
from typing import List, Any

nums: List[int] = [1, 2, 3]
chars: List[str] = ["a", "b", "c"]
mixed: List[Any] = [1, "two", 3.0]
empty: List[int] = []

Built from other types

python
list("abc")        # ['a', 'b', 'c']
list(range(5))     # [0, 1, 2, 3, 4]

3️⃣ Access and Modify Elements

python
nums: List[int] = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]

print(nums[0])     # 10
print(nums[-1])    # 50 (last)
nums[2] = 99       # update
print(nums)        # [10, 20, 99, 40, 50]

⚠️ Index Error if you go out of range:

python
# print(nums[10])  # ❌ IndexError

4️⃣ List Slicing

Slice syntax: list[start:end:step]

  • start → inclusive

  • end → exclusive

  • step → interval

python
nums: List[int] = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
print(nums[1:4])     # [2, 3, 4]
print(nums[:3])      # [1, 2, 3]
print(nums[::2])     # [1, 3, 5]
print(nums[::-1])    # reversed

5️⃣ List Operations

Concatenation & Repetition

python
nums: List[int] = [1, 2, 3]
nums2: List[int] = [4, 5]
combined: List[int] = nums + nums2      # [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
repeated: List[int] = nums * 2          # [1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3]

Membership Test

python
if 3 in nums:
    print("3 exists")

6️⃣ Common List Methods

python
nums: List[int] = [1, 2, 3]

nums.append(4)         # [1, 2, 3, 4]
nums.insert(1, 99)     # [1, 99, 2, 3, 4]
nums.extend([5, 6])    # [1, 99, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
nums.remove(99)        # removes first occurrence
nums.pop()             # removes last
nums.index(3)          # 3’s index
nums.count(2)          # how many 2’s
nums.sort()            # sorts in place
nums.reverse()         # reverses in place

Non-Mutating Versions

python
sorted_nums: List[int] = sorted(nums)   # returns new sorted list
reversed_nums: List[int] = list(reversed(nums))

7️⃣ Copying Lists (Critical Concept)

python
nums: List[int] = [1, 2, 3]
copy1: List[int] = nums.copy()
copy2: List[int] = nums[:]              # slicing copy
copy3: List[int] = list(nums)

⚠️ Shallow Copy Warning

python
matrix: List[List[int]] = [[1, 2], [3, 4]]
shallow: List[List[int]] = matrix.copy()
shallow[0][0] = 99
print(matrix)  # [[99, 2], [3, 4]]  -> inner lists shared

✅ Use deepcopy for independent copies:

python
import copy
deep: List[List[int]] = copy.deepcopy(matrix)

8️⃣ List Comprehensions (Pythonic Way)

Powerful shorthand for creating or transforming lists.

python
squares: List[int] = [x**2 for x in range(5)]
evens: List[int] = [x for x in range(10) if x % 2 == 0]
words: List[str] = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"]
lengths: List[int] = [len(w) for w in words]

9️⃣ Nested Lists (Matrices)

python
matrix: List[List[int]] = [
    [1, 2, 3],
    [4, 5, 6],
    [7, 8, 9],
]
print(matrix[1][2])  # 6

🧠 Use in LeetCode: for grid problems, BFS/DFS traversals, and 2D DP tables.

🔟 Iterating Over Lists

python
nums: List[int] = [10, 20, 30]

for num in nums:
    print(num)

for idx, val in enumerate(nums):
    print(idx, val)

🧮 11. Time Complexity of Common Operations

OperationAverage TimeExample
Access by indexO(1)nums[i]
Append at endO(1).append()
Insert/remove at middleO(n).insert(i,x)
Search for valueO(n)x in nums
SortO(n log n).sort()

🧠 12. Useful Built-in Functions for Lists

python
sum(nums)        # sum of elements
min(nums)        # smallest
max(nums)        # largest
len(nums)        # number of elements
all(nums)        # True if all non-zero/True
any(nums)        # True if any True

Now that you’ve mastered lists, it’s time for Lesson 3: Tuples — one of Python’s most underrated but powerful immutable types.
They’re key for data integrity, fast lookups, and hashable keys (for sets/dicts), all of which you’ll encounter on LeetCode.

🧩 LESSON 3: TUPLES IN PYTHON

1️⃣ What is a Tuple?

A tuple is an ordered, immutable sequence of elements.
It works like a list but cannot be changed after creation.

python
from typing import Tuple

numbers: Tuple[int, int, int] = (1, 2, 3)

✅ Ordered
✅ Allows duplicates
✅ Can contain mixed data types
🚫 Immutable (can’t modify elements after creation)

2️⃣ Creating Tuples

python
# Basic
nums: Tuple[int, int, int] = (1, 2, 3)

# Mixed types
person: Tuple[str, int, float] = ("Ali", 20, 88.5)

# Without parentheses (Python auto-detects)
coords: Tuple[int, int] = 10, 20

# Empty tuple
empty: Tuple[()] = ()

# Single-element tuple (Note the comma!)
single: Tuple[int] = (5,)

🧠 Why the comma matters:

python
x = (5)     # int
y = (5,)    # tuple

3️⃣ Accessing Tuple Elements

python
nums: Tuple[int, int, int] = (10, 20, 30)
print(nums[0])       # 10
print(nums[-1])      # 30
print(nums[1:])      # (20, 30)

⚠️ You can’t modify a tuple:

python
# nums[0] = 99  # ❌ TypeError

4️⃣ Tuple Packing and Unpacking

Packing

python
point: Tuple[int, int] = (10, 20)

Unpacking

python
x, y = point
print(x)  # 10
print(y)  # 20

You can also swap values easily:

python
a, b = 1, 2
a, b = b, a

5️⃣ Tuple in Loops

python
pairs: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], ...] = ((1, 2), (3, 4), (5, 6))

for x, y in pairs:
    print(f"x={x}, y={y}")

💡 This is used a lot in LeetCode — e.g., when iterating through coordinates or graph edges.

6️⃣ Tuple Methods

Tuples have only two methods (since they’re immutable):

python
nums: Tuple[int, int, int, int] = (1, 2, 2, 3)
print(nums.count(2))    # 2
print(nums.index(3))    # 3’s position (2)

7️⃣ Tuples as Dictionary Keys (Hashable)

Because tuples are immutable, they can be used as keys in dictionaries or elements in sets.

python
from typing import Dict, Tuple

location_data: Dict[Tuple[int, int], str] = {
    (10, 20): "Park",
    (15, 25): "Library"
}
print(location_data[(10, 20)])  # Park

❌ Lists can’t be used as keys — they’re mutable and unhashable.

8️⃣ Nested Tuples

python
matrix: Tuple[Tuple[int, int], Tuple[int, int]] = ((1, 2), (3, 4))
print(matrix[1][0])  # 3

Tuples can store tuples, creating multi-dimensional immutable structures.

9️⃣ Tuple Comprehensions? Nope ❌

Tuples don’t support comprehension directly — (x for x in range(5)) returns a generator, not a tuple.

python
t: Tuple[int, ...] = tuple(x for x in range(5))

🔟 Performance: Why Tuples Matter

FeatureListTuple
Mutable✅❌
Memory efficient❌✅
Hashable❌✅
Iteration speedSlowerFaster
Common usageDynamic dataFixed or key-like data

💡 In LeetCode: Tuples are used for:

  • Returning multiple values from functions

  • Marking visited cells in graphs (visited = set[(i, j)])

  • Coordinates in grids or matrices

🔢 11. Tuple Type Hints (Modern Way)

python
# Fixed-size tuple
point: Tuple[int, int] = (10, 20)

# Variable-length homogeneous tuple
nums: Tuple[int, ...] = (1, 2, 3, 4, 5)

The ellipsis (...) means “any number of elements of this type”.

🧮 12. Using Tuples to Return Multiple Values

python
from typing import Tuple

def divide(a: int, b: int) -> Tuple[int, int]:
    """Return quotient and remainder."""
    return a // b, a % b

q, r = divide(10, 3)
print(q, r)  # 3 1

This is a clean and Pythonic pattern — used all the time in interviews and contests.

🧩 Lesson 4: Sets and Frozensets

🔹 1. What is a Set?

A set in Python is an unordered collection of unique and immutable elements.

It’s very useful for:

  • Removing duplicates.

  • Fast membership testing (O(1) on average).

  • Mathematical operations like union, intersection, and difference.

🧠 Key Properties

PropertyDescription
MutableYou can add or remove elements.
UnorderedNo index-based access.
Unique ElementsNo duplicates allowed.
Fast LookupsMembership test is O(1).

🧰 Creating Sets

python
# With type hints
from typing import Set

# Method 1: Using curly braces
numbers: Set[int] = {1, 2, 3, 4}

# Method 2: Using set() constructor
letters: Set[str] = set(["a", "b", "c", "a"])  # duplicate 'a' ignored

print(numbers)  # {1, 2, 3, 4}
print(letters)  # {'a', 'b', 'c'}

⚠️ You cannot create an empty set using {} because that creates a dictionary.
Use set() instead:

python
empty_set: Set[int] = set()

⚙️ Common Set Methods

MethodDescriptionExample
add(x)Adds an elements.add(10)
remove(x)Removes an element (error if not found)s.remove(2)
discard(x)Removes if exists (no error if not)s.discard(2)
pop()Removes a random elements.pop()
clear()Empties the sets.clear()
len(s)Returns number of elementslen(s)
inCheck membershipif 5 in s:

🔁 Mathematical Operations

python
a: Set[int] = {1, 2, 3, 4}
b: Set[int] = {3, 4, 5, 6}

# Union
print(a | b)  # {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}
print(a.union(b))

# Intersection
print(a & b)  # {3, 4}
print(a.intersection(b))

# Difference
print(a - b)  # {1, 2}
print(a.difference(b))

# Symmetric Difference (elements not in both)
print(a ^ b)  # {1, 2, 5, 6}

⚡ Set Comprehensions

python
nums: Set[int] = {x for x in range(10) if x % 2 == 0}
print(nums)  # {0, 2, 4, 6, 8}

🔒 Frozenset

A frozenset is an immutable set.
You cannot modify it after creation — it’s hashable and can be used as a dictionary key or inside another set.

python
from typing import FrozenSet

fs: FrozenSet[int] = frozenset({1, 2, 3, 4})
print(fs)

# fs.add(5) ❌ ERROR — cannot modify frozenset

Used in LeetCode problems where you need sets as keys in a dictionary, like caching states in BFS/DFS.

🧠 Advanced Example (with typing)

python
from typing import Set, FrozenSet

def unique_characters(word: str) -> Set[str]:
    """Return all unique characters in a word."""
    return set(word)

def common_letters(words: Set[str]) -> Set[str]:
    """Find common letters between all given words."""
    return set.intersection(*(set(w) for w in words))

def immutable_example(items: Set[int]) -> FrozenSet[int]:
    """Return immutable version of a set."""
    return frozenset(items)

print(unique_characters("leetcode"))      # {'l', 'e', 't', 'c', 'o', 'd'}
print(common_letters({"hello", "world"})) # {'o', 'l'}
print(immutable_example({1, 2, 3}))       # frozenset({1, 2, 3})

🧩 Lesson 5: Dictionaries and TypedDicts

🔹 1. What is a Dictionary?

A dictionary (often called a hash map or associative array) stores data in key–value pairs.
Each key must be unique and immutable, while the value can be anything.

🧠 Key Properties

PropertyDescription
MutableYou can add, update, or delete entries.
Unordered (pre-3.7)From Python 3.7+, maintains insertion order.
Unique keysDuplicate keys overwrite previous ones.
Fast lookupsAverage time complexity O(1) for access, insertion, deletion.
Implemented as hash tablesJust like Maps in JavaScript or HashMaps in Java.

🧰 Creating Dictionaries

python
from typing import Dict

# Method 1: Literal syntax
person: Dict[str, str] = {
    "name": "Alice",
    "city": "London",
    "profession": "Engineer"
}

# Method 2: Using dict() constructor
student: Dict[str, int] = dict(name="Bob", age=21)

# Method 3: From pairs
pairs: Dict[str, int] = dict([("a", 1), ("b", 2)])

⚙️ Accessing and Modifying Data

python
person["city"] = "Paris"        # update
person["country"] = "France"    # add new key
print(person["name"])           # access value

# Safe access
print(person.get("age", "N/A"))  # returns "N/A" if key not found

⚠️ Accessing a missing key using person["age"] will raise a KeyError.

🧩 Removing Entries

python
person.pop("profession")  # removes and returns the value
del person["city"]        # delete key-value pair
person.clear()            # remove all

🔁 Iterating Over a Dictionary

python
scores: Dict[str, int] = {"Alice": 85, "Bob": 90, "Charlie": 78}

# Iterate over keys
for name in scores:
    print(name)

# Iterate over values
for score in scores.values():
    print(score)

# Iterate over key–value pairs
for name, score in scores.items():
    print(f"{name}: {score}")

💡 Membership Tests

python
if "Bob" in scores:
    print("Bob is present")

if 90 in scores.values():
    print("Someone scored 90")

🔐 Dictionary Comprehensions

python
squares: Dict[int, int] = {x: x**2 for x in range(1, 6)}
print(squares)  # {1: 1, 2: 4, 3: 9, 4: 16, 5: 25}

🧠 Nested Dictionaries

python

⚡ Real Example with Typing

python
from typing import Dict

def count_frequencies(nums: list[int]) -> Dict[int, int]:
    """Return frequency of each number."""
    freq: Dict[int, int] = {}
    for num in nums:
        freq[num] = freq.get(num, 0) + 1
    return freq

print(count_frequencies([1, 2, 2, 3, 1, 4]))
# Output: {1: 2, 2: 2, 3: 1, 4: 1}

🧩 Mini Problem Patterns

1. Two Sum

python
def two_sum(nums: list[int], target: int) -> list[int]:
    seen: Dict[int, int] = {}
    for i, num in enumerate(nums):
        diff = target - num
        if diff in seen:
            return [seen[diff], i]
        seen[num] = i
    return []

2. Word Count

python
def count_words(sentence: str) -> Dict[str, int]:
    words = sentence.split()
    freq: Dict[str, int] = {}
    for w in words:
        freq[w] = freq.get(w, 0) + 1
    return freq

🧩 Lesson 6: Tuples and NamedTuples

🔹 1. What is a Tuple?

A tuple is an ordered, immutable collection of elements.
Think of it as a “read-only list”.

You use tuples to:

  • Store fixed-size collections of related data.

  • Return multiple values from a function.

  • Use as dictionary keys or set elements (since they’re hashable).

🧠 Key Properties

PropertyDescription
OrderedMaintains order of elements
ImmutableCannot be changed after creation
HeterogeneousCan store elements of different types
HashableCan be used as dict/set keys (if elements are hashable)

🧰 Creating Tuples

python
from typing import Tuple

# Simple tuple
coords: Tuple[int, int] = (10, 20)

# Mixed-type tuple
student: Tuple[str, int, bool] = ("Alice", 21, True)

# Single-element tuple (must have a trailing comma)
one_item: Tuple[int] = (5,)

# Empty tuple
empty: Tuple[()] = ()

⚠️ Missing the trailing comma in (5) makes it an int, not a tuple.

⚙️ Accessing Elements

python
print(coords[0])   # 10
print(coords[1])   # 20

# Tuples support slicing
print(coords[:1])  # (10,)

🚀 Tuple Unpacking

You can assign elements directly to multiple variables.

python
point: Tuple[int, int] = (4, 9)
x, y = point
print(f"x={x}, y={y}")

🔁 Returning Multiple Values from a Function

python
from typing import Tuple

def divide(a: int, b: int) -> Tuple[int, int]:
    quotient = a // b
    remainder = a % b
    return quotient, remainder

q, r = divide(10, 3)
print(q, r)  # 3 1

⚡ Tuple Packing and Unpacking

python
# Packing
person = "Alice", 25, "London"  # automatic tuple

# Unpacking
name, age, city = person
print(name, age, city)

🧩 Using Tuples as Dictionary Keys

Since tuples are hashable, they can be used as keys in dictionaries:

python
from typing import Dict, Tuple

distances: Dict[Tuple[str, str], int] = {
    ("A", "B"): 5,
    ("B", "C"): 10,
}
print(distances[("A", "B")])  # 5

✅ Common in graph-based LeetCode problems (like shortestPath, networkDelayTime).

🧠 Tuple Methods

Tuples have only two methods:

  • count(x) → counts how many times x appears.

  • index(x) → returns the index of x.

python
nums: Tuple[int, ...] = (1, 2, 3, 2, 4)
print(nums.count(2))  # 2
print(nums.index(3))  # 2

🧩 NamedTuple

While tuples are simple, sometimes you want named fields for clarity — like a mini-class.

That’s where NamedTuple (from typing) comes in.

🧱 Creating NamedTuples

python
from typing import NamedTuple

class Point(NamedTuple):
    x: int
    y: int

p1 = Point(3, 4)
print(p1.x, p1.y)  # 3 4

✅ Immutable like tuples
✅ Access by name and index
✅ Fully type-checked
✅ Lighter than a class (used often in LeetCode geometry/grid problems)

⚙️ Accessing and Using NamedTuples

python
print(p1[0])   # 3
print(p1.x)    # 3
print(p1._asdict())  # {'x': 3, 'y': 4}

💡 Example: Tracking Coordinates in BFS

python
from typing import NamedTuple, List

class Cell(NamedTuple):
    row: int
    col: int

def get_neighbors(cell: Cell) -> List[Cell]:
    directions = [(1, 0), (-1, 0), (0, 1), (0, -1)]
    return [Cell(cell.row + dr, cell.col + dc) for dr, dc in directions]

neighbors = get_neighbors(Cell(2, 3))
for n in neighbors:
    print(n)

Performance⚡ FasterSlower (adds features)
Ideal ForImmutable, lightweight structuresMutable data objects

Return multiple results(min_val, max_val)

🔹 1. What is a List?

A list is an ordered, mutable, and dynamic collection in Python.

You can:

  • Add or remove elements anytime.

  • Store different data types (though same-type lists are ideal for LeetCode).

  • Use slicing, indexing, and comprehensions.

MutableYou can change elements

Allows duplicatesUnlike sets

🧩 Lesson 8: Strings & Advanced String Manipulation

🔹 1. What is a String?

A string is an immutable, ordered sequence of Unicode characters.

  • Immutable → once created, it can’t be changed.

  • Ordered → each character has an index.

  • Iterable → can loop through them like lists.

🔤 Declaring Strings

python
from typing import List

s1: str = "hello"
s2: str = 'world'
s3: str = """This is
a multiline string"""

📍 Accessing Characters

python
word: str = "python"

⚡ Example: Group Anagrams

python
from collections import defaultdict
from typing import List

def group_anagrams(words: List[str]) -> List[List[str]]:
    groups: defaultdict[str, List[str]] = defaultdict(list)
    for w in words:
        key = "".join(sorted(w))
        groups[key].append(w)
    return list(groups.values())

print(group_anagrams(["eat", "tea", "tan", "ate", "nat", "bat"]))

🧩 Combined: Set + Dict Example

🔥 Problem: Two Sum

python
def two_sum(nums: list[int], target: int) -> list[int]:
    seen: dict[int, int] = {}
    for i, n in enumerate(nums):
        complement = target - n
        if complement in seen:
            return [seen[complement], i]
        seen[n] = i
    return []

🧱 1️⃣ defaultdict

🔹 What It Is

defaultdict is a subclass of dict that automatically initializes missing keys with a default value.

🧰 Basic Example

python
from collections import defaultdict

freq: defaultdict[str, int] = defaultdict(int)

for ch in "banana":
    freq[ch] += 1

print(freq)  # defaultdict(<class 'int'>, {'b': 1, 'a': 3, 'n': 2})

✅ No need to check if key exists before updating — great for counting or grouping.

⚙️ Common Patterns

➤ Grouping items by a key

python
from typing import List
from collections import defaultdict

def group_by_length(words: List[str]) -> dict[int, list[str]]:
    groups: defaultdict[int, list[str]] = defaultdict(list)
    for w in words:
        groups[len(w)].append(w)
    return groups

print(group_by_length(["cat", "hi", "apple", "bat"]))
# {3: ['cat', 'bat'], 2: ['hi'], 5: ['apple']}

🧱 2️⃣ Counter

🔹 What It Is

A Counter is a subclass of dict specialized for counting hashable objects.

⚡ Example: Top K Frequent Elements

python
from collections import Counter
from typing import List

def top_k(nums: List[int], k: int) -> List[int]:
    count = Counter(nums)
    return [num for num, _ in count.most_common(k)]

print(top_k([1,1,1,2,2,3], 2))  # [1,2]

🧱 3️⃣ deque

🔹 What It Is

A deque (double-ended queue) is a list-like container that supports fast O(1) insertion and deletion from both ends.

Perfect for:

  • BFS (queue-based problems)

  • Sliding window

  • Caching

🧰 Basic Example

python
from collections import deque

dq: deque[int] = deque([1, 2, 3])
dq.append(4)
dq.appendleft(0)

print(dq)  # deque([0, 1, 2, 3, 4])

dq.pop()       # remove right
dq.popleft()   # remove left

⚙️ Use Case: BFS Traversal

python
from collections import deque
from typing import List

def bfs(start: int, graph: dict[int, List[int]]) -> List[int]:
    visited = set()
    queue = deque([start])
    result = []

    while queue:
        node = queue.popleft()
        if node not in visited:
            visited.add(node)
            result.append(node)
            queue.extend(graph[node])
    return result

graph = {1:[2,3], 2:[4], 3:[4], 4:[]}
print(bfs(1, graph))  # [1,2,3,4]

⚡ Sliding Window Example

python
from collections import deque
from typing import List

def max_sliding_window(nums: List[int], k: int) -> List[int]:
    dq: deque[int] = deque()
    result: List[int] = []

    for i, n in enumerate(nums):
        # Remove out-of-window
        while dq and dq[0] <= i - k:
            dq.popleft()

        # Maintain decreasing order
        while dq and nums[dq[-1]] < n:
            dq.pop()

        dq.append(i)

        # Window ready
        if i >= k - 1:
            result.append(nums[dq[0]])

    return result

🧱 4️⃣ heapq (Min-Heap / Priority Queue)

🔹 What It Is

heapq implements a binary heap, which gives O(log n) insertions and deletions — great for:

  • Getting min/max efficiently

  • Top-k problems

  • Dijkstra’s / A* algorithms

⚙️ Basic Example

python
import heapq

nums = [5, 2, 8, 1]
heapq.heapify(nums)
print(nums)  # [1,2,8,5] (heap order)

heapq.heappush(nums, 0)
print(heapq.heappop(nums))  # 0 (smallest element)

🔸 Max Heap Trick

Python has only a min-heap, so for max behavior, push negative values:

python
nums = [5, 2, 8, 1]
max_heap = [-n for n in nums]
heapq.heapify(max_heap)

print(-heapq.heappop(max_heap))  # 8

🔥 Example: Kth Largest Element

python
import heapq
from typing import List

def find_kth_largest(nums: List[int], k: int) -> int:
    return heapq.nlargest(k, nums)[-1]

print(find_kth_largest([3,2,1,5,6,4], 2))  # 5

💡 Example: Merge K Sorted Lists

python
import heapq
from typing import List

def merge_sorted(lists: List[List[int]]) -> List[int]:
    heap = []
    for i, lst in enumerate(lists):
        if lst:
            heapq.heappush(heap, (lst[0], i, 0))

    result = []
    while heap:
        val, li, ei = heapq.heappop(heap)
        result.append(val)
        if ei + 1 < len(lists[li]):
            heapq.heappush(heap, (lists[li][ei+1], li, ei+1))
    return result

print(merge_sorted([[1,4,5],[1,3,4],[2,6]]))

🧱 4️⃣ Lambda (Anonymous) Functions

🔹 What Are They?

Lambdas are small, inline functions without a name.

python

✅ Same as:

python
def square(x: int) -> int:
    return x * x

🔹 Lambda Syntax

python
lambda arguments: expression

Example:

python
add = lambda a, b: a + b
print(add(2, 3))  # 5

🔹 When to Use Lambdas

Use them for short, one-line, or temporary functions — usually as parameters.

⚡ Example 1: Sorting with Lambda

python
names = ["Alice", "Bob", "Charlie"]
names.sort(key=lambda name: len(name))
print(names)  # ['Bob', 'Alice', 'Charlie']

⚡ Example 2: Using map(), filter(), and reduce()

➤ map() — apply function to all elements

python
nums = [1, 2, 3, 4]

print(squared)  # [1, 4, 9, 16]

➤ filter() — keep elements meeting a condition

python
even_nums = list(filter(lambda x: x % 2 == 0, nums))
print(even_nums)  # [2, 4]

➤ reduce() — combine elements (must import)

python
from functools import reduce

product = reduce(lambda a, b: a * b, [1, 2, 3, 4])
print(product)  # 24

⚡ Example 3: Custom Sorts

python

    {"name": "Ali", "score": 85},
    {"name": "Sara", "score": 92},

🧩 Lesson 12: List, Dict, and Set Comprehensions

🧱 1️⃣ Introduction

Comprehensions are compact expressions for building collections from iterables.
They are used to filter, transform, or construct new lists, sets, or dictionaries in one line.

🔹 Traditional vs Comprehension Example

Regular way:

python
squares: list[int] = []
for i in range(5):
    squares.append(i * i)

Comprehension way:

python
squares = [i * i for i in range(5)]

✅ Same result, cleaner and faster.

🧱 2️⃣ List Comprehension

🔹 Basic Syntax

python
[expression for item in iterable]

🔹 Example

python
nums = [1, 2, 3, 4]
squares = [n ** 2 for n in nums]
print(squares)  # [1, 4, 9, 16]

🔹 With Condition

python
even_squares = [n ** 2 for n in nums if n % 2 == 0]
print(even_squares)  # [4, 16]

🔹 With Type Hint

python
from typing import List
nums: List[int] = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
odds: List[int] = [n for n in nums if n % 2 != 0]

⚙️ Nested List Comprehension

python
matrix = [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]]
flattened = [num for row in matrix for num in row]
print(flattened)  # [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]

⚡ Example: Cartesian Product

python
pairs = [(x, y) for x in [1, 2, 3] for y in [3, 1, 4] if x != y]
print(pairs)  # [(1,3), (1,4), (2,3), (2,1), (2,4), (3,1), (3,4)]

🧱 3️⃣ Dictionary Comprehension

🔹 Basic Syntax

python
{key_expr: value_expr for item in iterable}

🔹 Example: Squaring Numbers

python
squares_dict = {x: x ** 2 for x in range(5)}
print(squares_dict)  # {0: 0, 1: 1, 2: 4, 3: 9, 4: 16}

🔹 Example: Filtering with Condition

python
nums = {"a": 1, "b": 2, "c": 3, "d": 4}
even_nums = {k: v for k, v in nums.items() if v % 2 == 0}
print(even_nums)  # {'b': 2, 'd': 4}

🔹 Type Hint Example

python
from typing import Dict

squares: Dict[int, int] = {n: n ** 2 for n in range(1, 6)}

⚡ Reverse a Dictionary

python
original = {'a': 1, 'b': 2, 'c': 3}
reversed_dict = {v: k for k, v in original.items()}
print(reversed_dict)  # {1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c'}

🧱 4️⃣ Set Comprehension

🔹 Basic Syntax

python
{expression for item in iterable}

🔹 Example

python
nums = [1, 2, 2, 3, 3, 4]
unique_squares = {n ** 2 for n in nums}
print(unique_squares)  # {16, 1, 4, 9}

✅ Removes duplicates automatically (since sets only keep unique values).

⚙️ Filtering Example

python
even_set = {n for n in range(10) if n % 2 == 0}
print(even_set)  # {0, 2, 4, 6, 8}

🧱 5️⃣ Nested and Conditional Comprehensions

🔹 Nested Loops Example

python
matrix = [[1, 2], [3, 4], [5, 6]]
flatten = [n for row in matrix for n in row]
print(flatten)  # [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]

🔹 Conditional Expressions in Comprehension

python
nums = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
labels = ["even" if n % 2 == 0 else "odd" for n in nums]
print(labels)  # ['odd', 'even', 'odd', 'even', 'odd']

🔹 Complex Example (Matrix Transpose)

python
matrix = [[1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]]
transposed = [[row[i] for row in matrix] for i in range(3)]
print(transposed)  # [[1, 4], [2, 5], [3, 6]]

🧩 Lesson 13: Iterators and Generators

🧱 1️⃣ Iterables vs Iterators

Before learning generators, we must understand what iterators are.

🔹 Iterable

An iterable is any Python object that can be looped over (e.g. with for).

Examples:

python
nums = [1, 2, 3]       # list
word = "hello"         # string
dictionary = {"a": 1}  # dict

✅ You can use for loop on them.
But they are not iterators yet.

🔹 Iterator

An iterator is an object that remembers its position during iteration and can be manually advanced using next().

You can create one using iter():

python
nums = [1, 2, 3]
it = iter(nums)

print(next(it))  # 1
print(next(it))  # 2
print(next(it))  # 3

✅ When there are no more items, it raises:

nginx
StopIteration

⚙️ How It Works Under the Hood

When you do:

python
for n in nums:
    print(n)

Python automatically does this:

python
it = iter(nums)
while True:
    try:
        n = next(it)
        print(n)
    except StopIteration:
        break

💡 So loops are powered by iterators internally!

🧱 2️⃣ Creating Custom Iterators

You can make your own iterator by implementing two special methods:

  • __iter__() → returns the iterator object itself

  • __next__() → returns the next value

🔹 Example: Custom Counter

python
class Counter:
    def __init__(self, start: int, end: int):
        self.current = start
        self.end = end

    def __iter__(self):
        return self  # this object is the iterator

    def __next__(self) -> int:
        if self.current > self.end:
            raise StopIteration
        value = self.current
        self.current += 1
        return value

# Usage
for num in Counter(1, 5):
    print(num)

Output:

1
2
3
4
5

✅ This is how Python’s built-in iterators (like range) work internally.

🧱 3️⃣ Generators

Generators are special iterators created with functions and the yield keyword.

They allow you to produce items one at a time, instead of building a full list in memory.

🔹 Generator Function Example

python
from typing import Generator

def countdown(n: int) -> Generator[int, None, None]:
    while n > 0:
        yield n
        n -= 1

for num in countdown(5):
    print(num)

✅ Output:

5
4
3
2
1

💡 Each time Python reaches yield, it pauses the function and remembers its state.

🔹 Compare with Normal Function

Normal:

python
def countdown_list(n: int) -> list[int]:
    return [i for i in range(n, 0, -1)]

Generator:

python
def countdown_gen(n: int) -> Generator[int, None, None]:
    while n > 0:
        yield n
        n -= 1

✅ Generator uses O(1) memory,
while list uses O(n).

🧱 4️⃣ Generator Expressions

You can also create generators similar to list comprehensions — but with parentheses () instead of brackets [].

🔹 Example

python
gen = (x ** 2 for x in range(5))
print(next(gen))  # 0
print(next(gen))  # 1

✅ Unlike list comprehension, generator expressions don’t build the list in memory — they generate one value at a time.

🧱 5️⃣ yield from — Delegating to Sub-Generators

You can yield values from another generator easily using yield from.

🔹 Example

python
def sub_gen():
    yield 1
    yield 2

def main_gen():
    yield 0
    yield from sub_gen()  # yields values from another generator
    yield 3

print(list(main_gen()))  # [0, 1, 2, 3]

🧱 6️⃣ Practical LeetCode Applications

⚡ 1. Streaming Large Input

python
def read_lines(filename: str) -> Generator[str, None, None]:
    with open(filename) as f:
        for line in f:
            yield line.strip()

✅ Processes file line by line, no full load in memory.

⚡ 2. Infinite Sequence Generator

python
def infinite_counter() -> Generator[int, None, None]:
    n = 0
    while True:
        yield n
        n += 1

counter = infinite_counter()
print(next(counter))  # 0
print(next(counter))  # 1

✅ Keeps producing values forever — useful for testing or streams.

⚡ 3. Fibonacci Sequence

python
from typing import Generator

def fibonacci(limit: int) -> Generator[int, None, None]:
    a, b = 0, 1
    for _ in range(limit):
        yield a
        a, b = b, a + b

print(list(fibonacci(7)))  # [0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8]

⚡ 4. Generator Pipelines

python
def squares(nums: list[int]) -> Generator[int, None, None]:
    for n in nums:
        yield n * n

def even_only(nums: Generator[int, None, None]) -> Generator[int, None, None]:
    for n in nums:
        if n % 2 == 0:
            yield n

nums = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
print(list(even_only(squares(nums))))  # [4, 16]

✅ Efficiently chains generators — ideal for streaming or large datasets.

🧠 Lesson 14: Word Frequency Analyzer

🎯 Goal

We’ll create a Python program that:

  1. Takes a block of text (or a file),

  2. Cleans and normalizes it,

  3. Counts how often each word appears,

  4. Displays the top frequent words.

This project tests your knowledge of:

  • dict, Counter, defaultdict

  • string manipulation

  • loops, comprehensions

  • sorting

  • typing annotations

🧩 Concept Breakdown

1. Data Cleaning (Preprocessing)

Before counting, we must clean the text:

  • Convert to lowercase

  • Remove punctuation

  • Split into words

python
import re
from typing import List

def clean_text(text: str) -> List[str]:
    """
    Remove punctuation and split text into lowercase words.
    """
    cleaned_text = re.sub(r"[^\w\s]", "", text)  # remove punctuation
    words = cleaned_text.lower().split()
    return words

✅ Explanation:

  • re.sub() replaces punctuation with ""

  • .lower() normalizes case

  • .split() converts text to a list of words

2. Counting Word Frequency

Now we can count each word’s frequency.

🔹 Using a Regular Dictionary

python
from typing import Dict

def word_frequency(words: List[str]) -> Dict[str, int]:
    """
    Count frequency of each word using a regular dictionary.
    """
    freq: Dict[str, int] = {}
    for word in words:
        freq[word] = freq.get(word, 0) + 1
    return freq

🔹 Using collections.Counter (More Pythonic)

python
from collections import Counter

def word_frequency_counter(words: List[str]) -> Counter[str]:
    """
    Count frequency using Counter from collections.
    """
    return Counter(words)

3. Sorting by Frequency

To find the top N most frequent words:

python
from typing import List, Tuple

def top_n_words(freq: Dict[str, int], n: int) -> List[Tuple[str, int]]:
    """
    Return top n words sorted by frequency in descending order.
    """
    sorted_words = sorted(freq.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True)
    return sorted_words[:n]

4. Bringing It All Together

Here’s the complete project with all parts combined 👇

python
from typing import List, Dict, Tuple
from collections import Counter
import re

def clean_text(text: str) -> List[str]:
    cleaned_text = re.sub(r"[^\w\s]", "", text)
    return cleaned_text.lower().split()

def word_frequency(words: List[str]) -> Dict[str, int]:
    freq: Dict[str, int] = {}
    for word in words:
        freq[word] = freq.get(word, 0) + 1
    return freq

def top_n_words(freq: Dict[str, int], n: int) -> List[Tuple[str, int]]:
    return sorted(freq.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)[:n]

def main() -> None:
    text: str = """
    Python is great for data analysis. Python is easy to learn, and data analysis is fun with Python.
    """
    
    words: List[str] = clean_text(text)
    freq: Dict[str, int] = word_frequency(words)
    top_words: List[Tuple[str, int]] = top_n_words(freq, 3)
    
    print("Top 3 words:")
    for word, count in top_words:
        print(f"{word}: {count}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

🧠 Lesson 15: Simple Leaderboard System

🎯 Goal

We’ll create a leaderboard that:

  1. Keeps track of players and their scores.

  2. Updates scores dynamically.

  3. Shows top N players sorted by score.

  4. Demonstrates how to use classes, dict, and sorting with lambdas — all with type hints.

🧩 Concept Breakdown

1. Modeling the Player (Class Design)

Let’s define a Player class to represent each player on the leaderboard.

python
from typing import Any

class Player:
    def __init__(self, name: str, score: int = 0) -> None:
        self.name: str = name
        self.score: int = score

    def add_score(self, points: int) -> None:
        """Increase the player’s score by a given number of points."""
        self.score += points

    def __repr__(self) -> str:
        """Return a readable string representation."""
        return f"Player(name='{self.name}', score={self.score})"

✅ Explanation:

  • __init__: initializes player name and score.

  • add_score: allows updating scores dynamically.

  • __repr__: defines how the object is displayed when printed.

2. Managing the Leaderboard

We’ll store players in a dictionary {name: Player} for O(1) lookups.

python
from typing import Dict, List

class Leaderboard:
    def __init__(self) -> None:
        self.players: Dict[str, Player] = {}

    def add_player(self, name: str) -> None:
        """Add a new player if not already present."""
        if name not in self.players:
            self.players[name] = Player(name)
            print(f"✅ Player '{name}' added to the leaderboard.")
        else:
            print(f"⚠️ Player '{name}' already exists!")

    def update_score(self, name: str, points: int) -> None:
        """Update a player's score."""
        if name in self.players:
            self.players[name].add_score(points)
            print(f"🏆 {name}'s score updated to {self.players[name].score}")
        else:
            print(f"❌ Player '{name}' not found!")

    def top_players(self, n: int = 3) -> List[Player]:
        """Return the top N players sorted by score (descending)."""
        sorted_players = sorted(
            self.players.values(), key=lambda player: player.score, reverse=True
        )
        return sorted_players[:n]

    def display(self) -> None:
        """Print the full leaderboard."""
        print("\n🏅 Leaderboard:")
        for player in self.top_players(len(self.players)):
            print(f"{player.name}: {player.score}")

✅ Explanation:

  • self.players: stores all players.

  • add_player: adds a new player.

  • update_score: modifies existing player’s score.

  • top_players: returns sorted players (highest first).

  • display: prints the leaderboard.

3. Putting It All Together

Let’s bring everything together in a main function 👇

python
def main() -> None:
    leaderboard = Leaderboard()

    leaderboard.add_player("Alice")
    leaderboard.add_player("Bob")
    leaderboard.add_player("Charlie")

    leaderboard.update_score("Alice", 50)
    leaderboard.update_score("Bob", 80)
    leaderboard.update_score("Charlie", 40)
    leaderboard.update_score("Bob", 20)  # total 100

    leaderboard.display()

    print("\nTop 2 players:")
    for player in leaderboard.top_players(2):
        print(f"{player.name}: {player.score}")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
